nts a novel theoretical language – Williamsian, liberal and realist – to articulate this experience. Part I lays out the theoretical framework, while Part II examines how politicians, experts and citizens in illiberal regimes are confronted with role-specific, political-ethical challenges and how the various normative contexts of their roles shape their agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthoritarianism. 0aCivilization, ModernxPolitics and government. 0aDemocracyxPolitical aspects. 0aInternational relationsy21st century. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAndreas Schedler.  aAristotle.  aBernard Williams.  aCitizenship.  aExpertise.  aIlliberal regimes.  aPolitical ethics.  aPolitical office.  aPolitical realism.  aSteven Levitsky.1 aSzűcs, Zoltán Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614235140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526142351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526142351/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023